
[1]preface

   PREF'ACE, n. [L. proefatio; proe, before, and for, fari, fatus, to
   speak.] Something spoken as introductory to a discourse, or written as
   introductory to a book or essay, intended to inform the hearer or
   reader of the main design, or in general, of whatever is necessary to
   the understanding of the discourse, book or essay; a poem; an
   introduction or series of preliminary remarks.

   PREF'ACE, v.t. To introduce by preliminary remarks; as, to preface a
   book or discourse. The advocate prefaced his argument with a history of
   the case.

   1. To face; to cover; a ludicrous sense.

   Not prefacing old rags with plush.

                PREF'ACE, v.i. To say something introductory.
